gomodel:SYNGO_5208  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1b, 3e: immunofluorescence imaging of hippocampal neurons stained for endogenous Dock180 (DOCK1) and PSD95 (DLG4) showed partial co-localization. Stainings of Dock180 were apposed to presynaptic synapsin-1 (SYN1). Overexpressed FLAG-Dock180 localized to dendrites and spines.\n\nFigure 4: ELMO and Dock180 (DOCK1) form a complex in hippocampal neurons and function through activating Rac1. Overexpressed Dock180 increased spinogenesis.\n\nFigure 5-7: RhoG is required for spine formation, its activation leads to increased spine head size and functions through the ELMO1/Dock180/Rac pathway.. Experimental description: M&M: \"Neuronal Culture and Transfection - Hippocampal neuron cultures were prepared from embryonic day 19 rat embryos as described previously\"\n\nantibody:\nrabbit polyclonal anti-Dock180 (1:1000, provided by Dr. Matsuda)\ngoat polyclonal anti-Dock180 antibodies (1:100, N19 and C19, Santa Cruz Biotechnology)\nrabbit polyclonal anti-ELMO1 (1:1000, provided by Dr. Ravichandran)\ngoat polyclonal anti-ELMO1 (1:2000, Abcam)\n\nplasmids:\n\"FLAG-Dock180, Dock180-ISP, RhoG, and ELMO constructs were kindly provided by Kodi Ravichandran and have been described previously (24, 25, 33).\" PMID:12134158 which ultimately leads to PMID:8657152 --> Nucleotide BLAST confirms the human gene DOCK1 was targeted. BLAST of the protein sequence in PMID:8657152 Figure 2 yields uniprot accession Q14185 (human DOCK1).\n\nThe uniprot database currently does not contain a record for Rat DOCK1, so instead of annotating the endogenous protein we annotate the overexpressed species (human)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2023-03-03" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5208" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_9606" .

